<br>
NEW:  Episode 5 has now been added.  Enjoy.<br>
<br>
Episode 1. &quot;The Quest&quot;<br>
<br>
Lord Qyzar surveyed the young Iksar standing before him carefully. While it was true that Sarkokrul had been successful on every previous quest that he had been given, this would be the most difficult yet, and he wondered if the Shadow Knight would be up to it. The young dark knight was different from the rest, he shunned using the traditional shadow knight khukri and instead wielded his preferred wurm slayer, a large and cumbersome weapon Qyzar thought, but used with precision and deftness by this Iksar. Reports back to the Lord of the Iksar Shadow Knights had told of Sarkokrul easily cleaving the heads of Sarnak knights from their bodies in single precision thrusts. Yes this young Iksar was different from the rest, and that was the reason he stood before the Dark Knight Lord.<br>
<br>
“I have dispatched crusaders Golin and Fodcod to retrieve an ancient ceremonial dagger from within the underground crypt of Dalnir”, Lord Qyzar stated. “They have been gone for more than 3 full moon cycles and have yet to return, I fear that they have fallen prey to the Kly that inhabit that vile place now.” <br>
<br>
Qyzar watched Sarkokrul intently, looking for signs of apprehension from the young Iksar, but if there were any signs of emotion they were hidden behind the stoic face presented. Qyzar continued, “If the crusaders have fallen to the Kly in that place then they are minions to the Kly now and are forever gone, and should you see them they should be released from their torment.”<br>
<br>
Sarkokrul knew what was being communicated. Should he encounter either of the two fallen crusaders in his mission he would dispatch them to Cazic Thule and thus end their pain of failing to complete their assigned task.<br>
<br>
Qyzar noticed a perceptible rise in the corners of the Iksar’s mouth, and realized that his command would be fulfilled if Sarkokrul came upon the two crusaders. He nodded ever so perceptively at the young knight to show his approval, and then continued his orders. “You will proceed to the home of the Kly and retrieve the ceremonial dagger from their lair.” Qyzar continued, “I give you but one moon cycle to complete this task, you may take with you who you wish, but be cautious that they are strong of mind for the Kly are treacherous and have means of controlling those who are not of strong will, thus using them against you.”<br>
<br>
“I understand Lord” Sarkokrul snapped to attention in answering.<br>
<br>
“Return the dagger to me here, and the khukri that was to be Golin’s will be yours.” Qyzar stated flatly. “Who will you recruit to assist you on this?” He asked.<br>
<br>
“I can think of only one who I would trust my life to,” Sarkokrul announced quietly. “My brood brother.”<br>
<br>
Qyzar held in check his impulse to smile at this irreverent Iksar. It was highly uncommon for members of one brood to be indoctrinated in the ways of more than one arcane art, the two brothers had taken different paths in life, yet were joined by family blood. Young Talokrul was proving to be a formidable and adept Shaman within the Iksar shaman guild from what Qyzar had been told, and the two brothers together were said to be a most lethal combination. Stories of their raids on the Sarnak were becoming lore in Cabilis, not only for their success, but for their ferocity as well. The stories were told of two Iksar raiders invading the land of the dark elf outpost and leaving no less than seventy-five headless Sarnak corpses in their wake. The viciousness of the raid is said to be of Talokrul’s doing. The shaman had been caught by a small band of Sarnak near the lake of I’ll Omen as an initiate, and had been tortured for nearly three days, before he had escaped their small encampment, but not until they had removed his tongue by burning it out with the end of a heated sword. Since his return, the young Iksar was voiceless, but utterly vicious in any encounters with Sarnak since. <br>
<br>
Lord Qyzar knew that the two together were more than formidable, they were ferocious and single minded. “Go then young Shadow Knight and return within the moon cycle.” Qyzar stood and returned Sarkokrul’s salute.<br>
<br>
“May the spirit of Cabilis and Cazic Thule be with us.” Sarkokrul whispered, and quickly turned and left. He would seek out his brother, and once again they would go forth and taste the blood of the Iksar enemy.<br>
<br>
Episode 2. “The Joining”<br>
<br>
Sarkokrul slowly made his way through the shaman guild house on his way to the lower levels. He had passed through the guild hall a number of times since his brother’s return from the Lake, and each time the looks of surprise and nervousness from the number of adepts in the hall amused the young Shadow Knight. As he made his way to the door leading to the stairway a voice from behind demanded his attention.<br>
<br>
“Shadow Knight. What business requires your presence in our hall?” The voice of Hierophant Dexl demanded.<br>
<br>
“I have come for Talokrul Drokraken Excellency.” Sarkokrul answered solemnly, slightly bowing his head to the great Shaman in a show of respect as he spoke.<br>
<br>
Dexl viewed the Shadow Knight in front of him warily. Sarkokrul Drokraken had visited his brood brother a number of times, each followed with the two leaving the confines of the Shaman hall and Cabilis and venturing into the dangerous lands near the dark elf outpost on the far side of Warslik Woods and beyond. And each time they returned, there would be rumors of some calamity that had befallen an enemy of Iksar, and each calamity was of more violent, and vicious nature than the previous.<br>
<br>
“I understand that you and your brother recently visited the lands surrounding the high elf compound in Firiona Vie.” Hierophant Dexl stated more than asked of the Iksar before him.<br>
<br>
“Yes Excellency.” Sarkokrul replied.<br>
<br>
Dexl knew that asking the purpose of the excursion would be futile. Neither of these two of the clan Drokraken spoke much unless directly asked. The young Talokrul had had his tongue taken by low life Sarnak, and his older brother Sarkokrul either in sympathy with his younger sibling, or in respect to his pain had taken to hardly speaking out loud as well.<br>
<br>
From what Dexl had heard from the few travelers that were allowed to enter Cabilis and from brief discussions with Lord Qyzar, he had pieced together a fairly complete story of the results of the last “Drokraken” raid as they were beginning to be called. The crusaders had learned of a traitor in their guild and had sent the young Sarkokrul to investigate and eliminate him if he could learn his identity. That was the last time that Sarkokrul had visited the shaman guild hall in search of his brother, and they had left immediately and returned within only a week. According to what Qyzar had said, the two had located the traitor, and after killing the drachnid spy whom he was dealing with the two had disposed of the traitor crusader, and then left an undeniable message to the drachnid and high elves of their recent presence. <br>
<br>
The two had severed the torso of the drachnid and placed the torso and lower body on spikes inside the area of the valley controlled by the spider people. The traitor who had been masquerading as one of the elf trackers of the outpost, they staked his headless body just outside the great bridge surrounded by seven or eight bodies of dead pilgrims who had the unfortunate luck to encounter the two as they prepared their message. Needless to say the spider rider and high elf compounds were thrown into panic at the impunity of an Iksar raid so deep into their lands, and at the viciousness of the resultant messages. Qyzar said that Sarkokrul had returned the stolen tomb to the Shadow Knight Lord and that the family of the traitorous crusader had been given a present of the severed head to ensure his shame was theirs as well.<br>
<br>
Dexl shook the images from his mind and returned his attention to Sarkokrul. “Your brother is in his room in meditation. Shall I send an adept to fetch him?”<br>
<br>
“No Excellency, I must speak to him alone.” Replied Sarkokrul as he bowed ever so slightly and quickly made his way through the door leading to the stairs.<br>
<br>
Hierophant Dexl thought to himself that he must watch the brothers closely, Talokrul was becoming an excellent shaman, and Sarkokrul was becoming a strong force in the Shadow Knight guild. While leaders of the two guilds maintained a mutual respect, they were always just under the surface at odds with each other. Should open guild war breakout, Dexl knew that only the brood blood ties of the Drokraken clan would direct the way of the two young Iksar. And the two were becoming a powerful force to be reckoned with in such a case. Hierophant Dexl thought to himself in retrospect. Should a war between shaman and shadow knight develop, it would be best for both sides if the two Drokraken were removed from any equation at the outset. <br>
<br>
Sarkokrul stood before the rough wood door deep below the shaman guild hall. A light tap of the sword hilt to the frame announced his presence to the room’s occupant. Footsteps on the other side approached the door, and slowly it opened to reveal his brother in full armor.<br>
<br>
“I see you expected me again brother.” Sarkokrul stated with a bit of surprise once again in his voice. How his brother knew of his visits before hand puzzled Sarkokrul. If there was one thing the Shadow Knight prided himself on was being unpredictable. Yet his brother always seemed to anticipate his arrivals and be waiting in full armor readiness.<br>
<br>
Talokrul nodded, and with a slight smirk crossing his face made a small number of hand gestures and then pointed back down the hall from which Sarkokrul had come.<br>
<br>
“We go to meet the Kly, and should be back within the next moon.” Sarkokrul quietly answered to his brothers sign language questions. Since the unfortunate encounter with the Sarnak by the Lake, the two brothers had developed a simple sign language between them to communicate. Though seldom was even that amount of communication necessary when on the hunt. The two had a natural sense bond between them, and they always anticipated each other precisely.<br>
<br>
The two Iksar quickly strode up the stairs and out of the guild hall, ignoring the inquisitive glances of the remaining Hierophants and Adepts scattered about in prayer or meditation. Sarkokrul however, noticed the cold and penetrating gaze of Hierophant Dexl as he strode out the gate. There was something about his gaze that troubled Sarkokrul. A small hand gesture from Talokrul confirmed that he had the same sense. Whatever troubled them about it would have to wait. They were a good three day trip from the Kly stronghold, and they would need to be careful of the Giant stronghold along the way.<br>
<br>
The two stopped just outside the gates of Cabilis to inspect their packs, and ensured that all the proper provisions were taken care of.<br>
<br>
“Shall we go then brother?” Sarkokrul whispered quietly into the night air.<br>
<br>
A perceived nod of his brother’s head told him they were ready for their journey. Sarkokrul stepped forward but felt the firm grasp of Talokrul’s hand on his arm. Turning to face his brother, Sarkokrul could read the face before him and knew the question being asked.<br>
<br>
“Yes brother, the family of Goxnok received our present.” Sarkokrul stated flatly, and stepped off along the trail leading to the west. <br>
<br>
A look of satisfaction crept across the young shaman’s face, and he quickly stepped off behind his brother. Once again they were together and on the hunt he thought to himself. The blood of the Kly would be new to them, but he was sure that they would see much of it. And quickly the two Iksar disappeared from view from the entrance to Cabilis.<br>
