<br>
A warm breeze coming off of the hills and out to sea covered the two Iksar as they knelt hidden in the bushy growth off to the side of the masked cave entrance.  Sarkokrul and Talokrul had been watching the entrance to the cave now for a couple of days, noting the comings and goings of the Kly inhabitants, evaluating relative risks and their soon to be opponents.  While there was only an occasional excursion of the Kly from their haven, there had been a large party of Kly returning to the den the day before, with obvious prisoners or slaves.  They had quickly herded them into the entrance without either Iksar obtaining a good view for any type of recognition.  The wind had been blowing across their position from the west so that even a sniff of the breeze could not provide a clue as to the poor unfortunates being led presumably to their demise.<br>
<br>
“It will be daylight soon brother, we should start.” Whispered the Shadow Knight to his brother Shaman.  “They seem to be most active during the night so we should have some advantage in our first encounters.”<br>
<br>
Talokrul nodded his head in agreement, while continuing his observations of the cave entrance.<br>
<br>
Slowly, without a sound to be heard the two began gathering their provisions and stilling themselves for the upcoming raid.  Once packed and prepared, each of them started a quick flurry of hand gestures.<br>
<br>
Wisps of air encircled the two, and slowly their body’s began to shimmer and then fade into the background of the surrounding fauna.  Within a few seconds, all that could be seen where they were standing was the telltale signs of bent grass, lightly marking their presence. <br>
<br>
Quickly making their way into the cave, they followed the carved tunnel for a few minutes until it diverged into two opposite intersecting paths.  Talokrul sniffed the air about him and gave a small hiss as he started down the path leading directly to the right.  Sarkokrul followed his brother’s lead and took a quick sniff of the air as he moved to follow his brother, and could discern the scents of the Kly and slaves who had passed through the cave in the intervening days.<br>
<br>
Sarkokrul, following closely behind his brother, tried to recognize the various scents wafting in the air around him.  The Kly scents were easy, for they had the peculiar odor of Sarnak about them.  Sarkokrul figured the Kly were a relative race to the Sarnak, and decided that they would be easily tracked once they entered the crypt proper.  The other scents combined into a mishmash of odors from nearly every race he had encountered in his journeys.  Dwarf, Iksar, Elf, Gnome, Erudite, and even a scent of Dark Elf could be determined.    These he figured were the slave population used by the Kly.  Unlike the Sarnak, the Kly appeared to be significantly more intelligent, which made them significantly more dangerous.<br>
<br>
Slowly, the walls of the rough tunnel began to show signs of more careful excavation.  As the two continued down the tunnel, the walls began to be more smoothed and worked, eventually opening out into a well formed hallway wide enough for the two iksar to walk abreast as they continued.<br>
<br>
As the two Iksar rounded a small bend in the hallway, the tunnel split into two separate paths.  Carefully examining the floor of the hallway, Sarkokrul noticed that the floor of the two paths appeared equally worn as opposed to the tunnel they had just been in.  Sarkokrul took a quick sniff of the air, the scent of Kly was weak, and only the scents of the slave races could be strongly noticed.   <br>
<br>
Following the contours of the winding hallway Sarkokrul began to hear the sound of movement farther down the passageway.  Moving silently along the wall, he came to an abrupt end to the hall.  Peering cautiously around the corner, he noticed that the hallway quickly expanded into a large cavern, with oil lamps lining the walls at various intervals.  At the far end of the cavern, a large massive structure stood lighted against the surrounding darkness.  The large columns easily fifty to 60 feet high, supported a massive and highly decorated roof structure, giving the building the appearance of a temple.  The steps leading up and through the large columns ended at a large ornate entrance with a much more intense light emanating from within.<br>
<br>
As Sarkokrul stood quietly surveying the massive temple, he noticed a number of small creatures hovering in and around the columns.  From the distance they seemed to behave like fish swimming in a lake, but Sarkokrul knew that these creatures were floating in the air as if by some magical power.  Taking note of the positions of the creatures and following their ebbs and flows around the entrance to the temple complex, Sarkokrul counted at least three of the creatures.<br>
<br>
Moving his focus back into the large cavern a number of creatures could be seen simply standing in various reposes throughout the large expanse of the cave.  Another four creatures occupied the cavern in addition to the floating things near the temple.  A Tier’dal stood quietly in the far corner of the cave nearest the steps, a skeleton at it’s side.  On the far right, a single Dwarf stood motionless.  Closer to the Iksar, two Goblins faced each other in a trance like state, neither moving or speaking.<br>
<br>
“Prepare yourself brother.”  Stated Sarkokrul flatly, holding up two fingers and gesturing to the area occupied by the two Goblins.<br>
<br>
Talokrul nodded his understanding, and prepared for the attack.<br>
<br>
Quickly moving to their right and along the wall of the cave, the two Iksar closed on the unwary Goblins.  Sarkokrul reached his target first.  Grasping the face of the Goblin from behind, he quickly brought the end of the large blade around in front of the unsuspecting beast and brought the blade effortlessly across the defenseless creatures neck, severing arteries, muscle, and wind pipe in a single effortless stroke.  A small gurgle of a sound could be heard, but not loud enough to be heard more than a couple feet away.  The first of the two Goblins slumped to the floor of the cave, drowning in it’s own blood.<br>
<br>
Talokrul timed his thrust of the Chokidai with the rapid movements of his Shadow Knight brother.  The long slender point of the weapon easily entered the Goblin, sliding through the spaces between ribs as they joined the backbone near the spine of the creature.  An instant later, with an additional thrust of the weapon, it continued its course through the chest cavity of the creature, puncturing the lungs, effectively silencing any possible sounds the beast may have attempted to utter.  Pushing farther the Chokidai found the heart and burst it within the body of the creature.  The body of the Goblin shuddered as the point exited the heart and struck the backside of the creatures breastbone, and it slowly fell to it’s knees and expired.<br>
Talokrul extracted the weapon and heard the sound of air rushing into the vacated wound.<br>
<br>
The two iksar now visible to all who could see in the dim lights turned and faced the remaining Tier’dal and Dwarf.  Prepared for an immediate attack by the two creatures, Sarkokrul was surprised to see that they had not moved even slightly.  The Tier’dal stood exactly where she had been, and the same was true of the Dwarf farther along the wall to the right.  The only movement from any of the remaining creatures in the cave that Sarkokrul could determine was the continual swimming of the beasts near the columns.<br>
<br>
“Either they will not move against us, or they can not move against us.”  Whispered Sarkokrul to his brother.<br>
<br>
Talokrul gestured quickly with his hands explaining what he planned to do.  Sarkokrul nodded his agreement, and pulled his bow from the quiver and notched an arrow.  <br>
<br>
Talokrul stood and walked directly to a point halfway between the two living statues, prepared to move in either direction should movement be forthcoming.  As he reached the center point of this first move, neither of the creatures moved, nor even gave notice of his presence.  Cautiously moving sideways, Talokrul neared the Tier’dal until he was but a few feet away and standing directly in front of it.  Still there was no movement in defense or attack from the creature.<br>
<br>
Talokrul gestured quickly and a purple haze enveloped the skeleton standing next to the Dark Elf, the ground seeming to come to life and engulf the feet and legs forming a hard grasp of the creature ensuring it’s inability to move farther.  Sarkokrul let loose the notched arrow at the Tier’dal, the bladed point entered the Dark Elf just below the center of the creature’s right eye and exploded the skull as it exited the back side.  A shower of bone and blood splattering against the cave wall behind it.  The force of the impact threw the creature backwards against the wall, a dull thud reverberating through the large cave.<br>
<br>
The skeleton seemed at that instant to come to life and struggle against the grasp of the ground surrounding it’s feet and legs, lunging in a vain attempt to reach the Iksar Shaman standing only a few feet away.  Talokrul stepped back and then forward bringing the Chokidai around in a large swinging arc impacting on the dead creature’s skull.  The brittle bone shattered at the impact, and the remaining skeletal form crumpled to the ground in a pile of dust.<br>
<br>
Sarkokrul glanced at the remaining Dwarf.  It still had not moved during the second attack.  The lack of action puzzled the Shadow Knight.  “What is the purpose of having these evidently soulless creatures as guards, when they stand in silence without defending themselves.”  Sarkokrul thought to himself.<br>
<br>
Sarkokrul moved his focus to the air swimming creatures near the steps, relegating the stoic Dwarf to the category of “non threat”.  Cautiously Sarkokrul and Talokrul approached the bottom of the giant steps watching the apparently aimless swimming of the three rather benign looking beasts.  Sarkokrul had never seen creatures such as these in his travels before, and cautiously watched them swim in the air around the columns at the top of the steps.  The creatures had dull gray and tan bodies, about the size of an Iksar torso, with long whip like tails streaming behind them.  No facial features could be discerned, nor limbs of any kind.  A small crease ran from one side of the front around to the other side, but Sarkokrul could not determine if this was an indication of a mouth as such or just an marking along the sides of the creature.   <br>
<br>
Sarkokrul cautiously placed his foot on the first step.  Quickly he noticed a change in the nearest floating creature.  It had turned sharply and stopped, the front of the creature facing directly at the intruding Shadow Knight.<br>
<br>
The long crease around the edge of the creature began to open revealing several rows of large dagger sharp teeth.  As far as Sarkokrul could tell, the entire creature with the exception of the whip tail was nothing more than a ravenous mouth designed to rip it’s prey into small pieces of easily digestible pieces.  <br>
<br>
The nearest creature moved through the air quickly towards Sarkokrul, mouth gapping showing the many rows of sharp teeth each nearly the width of his hand long.  Sarkokrul thrust the wurmslayer forward intending to impale the creature on its two pronged point.  But the creature moved with exceptional quickness and agility and circled the reaching point of the weapon, closed with the Shadow Knight and bit savagely down on Sarkokrul’s left arm just below the shoulder.  The chain armor kept the teeth from penetrating the Iksar’s arm, but the strength of the jaws of the creature caused a sharp pain to rocket to Sarkokrul’s brain.<br>
<br>
Sarkokrul released his grasp of his blade with his left hand and brought the weapon around and under the creature with his right, slicing the underbelly of the creature, releasing the beasts internal organs from their floating encasement.  At the same time a blue hue enveloped the creature, causing an involuntary shudder at the force of the cold blast unleashed by Talokrul.  The jaws of the creature became slack, releasing Sarkokrul’s arm from it’s grasp and sunk slowly to the ground, quivering in it’s own internal organs as it died.<br>
<br>
Sarkokrul noticed another of the creatures beginning its attack, and the third moving to the left in an attempt to gain access to their flank.  Remembering the agility of the first creature, Sarkokrul waited until the second beast was nearly upon him before sidestepping to his right bringing his blade down across the back of the creature, opening a large gaping wound.  As the blade struck flesh, the ravenous looking beast turned sharply, attacking the Shadow Knight under the damaged left arm.   However, the creature was unable to acquire flesh, but the force of the impact knocked Sarkokrul to one knee, forcing the air from his lungs in a loud hiss.<br>
<br>
Talokrul saw his brother slump to one knee at the force of the second creature’s attack, but stayed concentrated on the third creature rapidly approaching from the left.  Talokrul gestured quickly, the blue hue of the cold force striking the creature head on stopping it’s advance.  Moving quickly while the creature sat stunned, Talokrul bashed the mouth of the creature with his shield forcing the front up and away from him, exposing the soft underbelly of the creature to his weapon.  Which penetrated easily from beneath, and exiting the top of the creature acting as a skewer, locking the large mouth shut.  The creature flailed against the air around it, trying to free itself from the impalement, but to no avail.  Slowly, Talokrul could feel the life of the creature ebb away as it slowly settled on the ground on it’s back, the handle of the Chokidai pointing toward the ceiling of the cavern.<br>
<br>
Sarkokrul gasp for air, regained his feet, and faced the attacking creature preparing for the next lung.  The creature was moving slower now due to it’s wound, but was still intent on it’s prey.  The beast came directly at Sarkokrul at eye level, allowing Sarkokrul to see deep within the large dark mouth of the beast.  Side stepping to the right to protect his now broken left arm, the Shadow Knight thrust the blade tip inside the creatures mouth penetrating the roof and exiting through the previous wound.  The beast thrashed violently on the end of the large blade, like a fish on the end of a fishing pole, the tail and body convulsing in opposite directions.  Sarkokrul spoke a quick chant, his hands glowing in a yellow hue as he spoke.  A crease of a smile crossed the Shadow Knight’s face as the remaining life force of the creature passed through the blade and into the Iksar.  The life drained out of the creature, it slowly sunk to the ground.<br>
<br>
Sarkokrul started to remove the arm protector over his broken left arm when a movement out of the corner of his eye alerted him to the presence of the oncoming Dwarf.  Turning to face the attack, Sarkokrul noticed the fury in the eyes of the approaching Dwarf, filling his expression with the rage of the tormented.  The eyes were wide, the mouth snarled, as if filled with true blood hate.<br>
<br>
Sarkokrul stood his ground, awaiting the force of the attack he knew to be coming.  The Dwarf let out a scream of rage and anger, that filled the cavern, and leapt upon the Shadow Knight.  As the Dwarf leapt, Sarkokrul closed his eyes and struck the oncoming creature with the palm of his hand, fingers spread, making contact directly over the attacking Dwarf’s heart.  The room exploded in a crackling sound of thunder and the Dwarf fell writhing in pain on the ground at Sarkokrul’s feet.<br>
<br>
Sarkokrul stepped forward raising the sword to strike the killing blow.  As he focused on the face of the Dwarf, Sarkokrul recognized the Dwarf as cleric Stubble Fey, whom he and his brother had shared camp with only a few nights before.  The shock of recognition, caused the Shadow Knight to slowly lower his weapon.<br>
<br>
“Please. Kill me friend.  Please.” Begged Stubble Fey as he lay on the floor before the two Iksar.   His face alternating between rage and pain.  “Please.” He sobbed.<br>
<br>
Sarkokrul raised his weapon again and brought it down against the neck of his recent acquaintance, easily cleaving the head from the body.<br>
<br>
The two Iksar turned and faced each other.  Neither needing to speak or attempt to speak of what had just taken place.  The Kly had captured the cleric and possibly the rest of the small group, and had been the slaves taken into the cave the night before.  The rage on the face of the Dwarf spoke of his torment and requested relief from it’s bond.  <br>
<br>
Sarkokrul thought to himself, “What manner of creatures are these Kly, that they can take the mind of others and move them to their own purpose?”<br>
<br>
The two iksar moved around the side of the temple, out of sight of the entrance, where Talokrul began to tend to the broken arm of his brother.  The small alcove was obviously unused from the thick layer of dust on the floor.<br>
<br>
“ We must be more vigilant brother.”  Said Sarkokrul, “The treachery we face appears to be great indeed.”<br>
<br>
Talokrul nodded in quiet agreement.<br>
<br>
Sarkokrul looked at his arm carefully.  The regeneration would take some time.  They would rest in the alcove and continue once it had healed completely.   Sarkokrul closed his eyes and saw the anguished face of Stubble Fey in his mind’s eye, and slowly slipped off to sleep.<br>
