<br>
The damp, gray walls of the alcove came into focus as Sarkokrul rose from his injury induced sleep.  Looking around the small enclosure, he could see the form of his brother quietly sitting on his haunches facing out from their hiding place, surveying the path back to the temple.<br>
<br>
“Any movement brother?” asked Sarkokrul quietly.<br>
<br>
Talokrul slowly looked over his shoulder and nodded negatively.  Moving quietly back into the alcove, Talokrul gestured with his hands in a deliberate manner, quickly revealing the happenings during his brother’s rest.<br>
<br>
During the night a small band of Tier’Dal had entered the entrance way to the temple and engaged in a fierce battle with the guards outside.  After defeating the controlled guards, they had moved into the temple and had not returned, now some five hours hence.<br>
<br>
“If they are within the crypt they may possibly keep the occupants busy while we perform our task.”  Stated Sarkokrul flatly as he adjusted his armor and supply sacks about him.<br>
<br>
Talokrul nodded in agreement, and pointed towards the injured arm.<br>
<br>
“It is healed sufficiently, we should not delay in taking the opportunity.”  Replied Sarkokrul.<br>
<br>
Wisps of air began to encircled the two, and slowly their body’s began to shimmer and then fade into the background of the surrounding cave. Within a few seconds, all that could be seen where they were standing was the telltale disturbances in the thick layer of dust on the floor of the unused alcove.<br>
<br>
Moving forward to the edge of the temple, the two could see no sign of guards or the floating beasts that they had encountered earlier.  Carefully, they climbed the stairs of the temple and moved inside the massive entranceway.   As they moved forward the passage diverted into opposite leading halls which curved away out of sight preventing a clear view of any possible dangers.<br>
<br>
Sarkokrul lifted his head and took a brief sniff of the stale air.  There were no indications of strong scent in the air, indicating that there were no guards or other creatures lurking nearby.  Sarkokrul motioned quickly, and stepped forward and down the curving passage to the right.<br>
<br>
Following the curving hall, the two quickly came to a large oval room, which it was obvious that the two halls came back to confluence at.  The remains of three of the floating beasts littered the floor around a central ornate structure.   Moving closer Sarkokrul noticed that the top of the structure was open, allowing him to peer down some twenty feet to a pool in what looked like a much larger room below.<br>
<br>
Sarkokrul climbed quietly on to the edge of the wall surrounding the opening and listened for signs of movement below.  <br>
<br>
Detecting no movement or sounds from below, Sarkokrul stepped off of the edge landing with a rather large splash in the pool below.  Looking quickly around the large room, he detected no movement or subsequent danger.  A quick movement of his arm in signal to his brother, quickly resulted in a second loud splash in the pool as Talokrul joined his brother in the middle of the room.<br>
<br>
Taking more care in his second perusal of the room, he quickly focused on the remains of the Tier’Dal who had entered before them.  They had evidently entered in the same manner but had quickly been set upon by what ever guard contingent had been present at the time.  <br>
<br>
The bodies lay in a small semi circle surrounding the pool.  Sarkokrul examined the nearest Tier’Dal noting the large blistered areas on the body, indicating the attack had been from a strong magical force.  As he examined the head area, he noticed that the back of the skull had been fractured and a segment of brain had been removed, and a glowing ball inserted within.  The ball slowly pulsed with an incandescent light.  As Sarkokrul observed, small tentacles spread from the orb and began attaching themselves to various portions of the dead Tier’Dal brain.<br>
<br>
“So that is how they control their slaves.” Sarkokrul mused to himself quietly.  <br>
<br>
Realizing, that the orb performed some type of regeneration effect on the dead creature as well, Sarkokrul moved quickly to the one entrance door to the room signaling for his brother to follow.  Moving through the doorway the two entered a small hall area that was still under some type of construction, but was well outside the hearing or sight range of the now regenerating and controlled Tier’Dal, and out of the long view of the connecting hall.<br>
<br>
“We will have to dispatch them again brother, when we make our escape from this place.” Stated Sarkokrul.  Talokrul nodded in agreement.<br>
<br>
As the two iksar watched the flickers of life enter the bodies of the previously deceased Tier’Dal, a footstep alerted Sarkokrul to an approaching danger.  <br>
<br>
Moving quickly, Sarkokrul brought the large blade around and thrust it firmly towards the head of the approaching figure.  The crack of bone could be heard as the sword tip entered just underneath the jaw of the unsuspecting creature, and penetrated into the skull in an upward thrust.  The knees of the creature gave out and the creature slumped to the floor, never knowing the reason, or instrument of its death.<br>
<br>
Dragging the corpse of the disposed of Kly around the corner, and out of view of the long hall, Sarkokrul noticed a sharp jagged piece of metal laying on the floor near where the Kly had fallen.  Picking it up and examining it, he realized that it was a metal shard from a rather ornate larger weapon.  Sarkokrul placed the piece in his pack and started preparations for their next movement.<br>
<br>
Once more under the effects of the cloaking magic, the two moved farther into the maze of corridors, and hallways of the crypt.  Occasionally passing creatures, obviously under the influence of the implanted orbs, neither Sarkokrul nor Talokrul made any attempt to distract or interfere with their wretched existence.  Rounding another of the many sweeping bends in the long hallways that permeated the crypt they came to a small circular room with finely ornate murals and gilded trappings.  The room sat off to one side of the hall, conspicuously separated from the surrounding rooms.  Talokrul made a few gestures, indicating that the room would provide a secluded position from which to foray into the rest of the crypt and return for rest and sustenance. <br>
<br>
“Aye brother, we will set up here.” Answered Sarkokrul. “It appears to be unused and particularly isolated from the remainder.”<br>
<br>
Squatting on their haunches the two iksar slowly pulled some rations of earthworm munch and blood water from their packs, quietly eating, replenishing their strength, but vigilant for any movement or sound from the nearby hallway.<br>
<br>
As Sarkokrul placed a portion of the earthworm munch in his mouth, a small breeze swept through the small room.  Sarkokrul lifted his snout to the air and sniffed for indications of nearby scent.  Nothing distinguishable could be picked out, but the breeze began to grow stronger.  Ever so slightly, the two iksar noticed small particles of sand on the floor of the room beginning to swirl in a clockwise circle in the middle of the room.  Slowly, the two rose to their feet, and drew weapons in preparation for some unseen, unknown approaching danger.<br>
<br>
The breeze intensified in its swirling motion in the center of the room, forming a small vortex at the base where it met the stone floor.  As Sarkokrul watched, a shape began to appear within the wisps of dust, and the unmistakable outline of a Iksar could be seen within the swirling mass of air.<br>
<br>
Slowly the swirling air settled, revealing the ghostly image of an Iksar Shadow Knight.  The form translucent, and shifting in the dim light, stood quietly, both in this world and another.   No movement to attack could be seen, so Sarkokrul slowly stepped forward to the shape before him.<br>
<br>
“What manner of deception is this?” Asked Sarkokrul.  “Are we to be frightened like little broodlings?”<br>
<br>
The shape before him turned slowly to face him ever slightly shifting above the floor never touching it.<br>
<br>
“Hark these words Shadow Knight, for my fate is yours soon.”  The figure gasped in a grating, guttural voice.<br>
<br>
Sarkokrul stood firm in his position ensuring that the figure’s form would pass across his body, allowing him to sense the cold hand of death gripping the tormented soul before him. <br>
<br>
The form before him continued. “I was like you once, confident in my skills. And the faith and power of Cazic Thule ran strong through my being.”  A grimace and look of anguish quickly enveloped the ghostly figure.  “But my failure has condemned me.  Just as your failure will condemn you to wander the twilight world, never feeling the sunlight, the scent of the forest, or the feel of the earth beneath your feet.”<br>
<br>
“What failure do you speak of Crusader?” Snapped Sarkokrul. “I have not failed, nor will I, by Cazic Thule I do swear!”<br>
<br>
A small smile formed on the face of the ghostly crusader. “Ah then you do not seek the mystical dagger Visceral?”   <br>
<br>
“Perhaps.” Responded Sarkokrul, “But what is that to you?”<br>
<br>
“I also took the quest to return the magical dagger to our home, as you have done.” Replied the Crusader. “My failure in that mission, has placed me in the nether realm between life and death, as you shall be as well.”<br>
<br>
“What is your name Crusader, so that I may mark your words, and prove you weak in the face of your prophecy?” Sarkokrul responded in defiant tones.<br>
<br>
“My name is of no consequence to you young one.” Replied the ghostly image. “But if it gives you strength to know who prophesies your end, then let it be known.  My name is Golin, vassal of Lord Qyzar.”<br>
<br>
Sarkokrul remembered the directive of Lord Qyzar when agreeing to the quest within the walls of Cabilis. “If the crusaders have fallen to the Kly in that place then they are minions to the Kly now and are forever gone, and should you see them they should be released from their torment.” Qyzar had said.  Sarkokrul contemplated the release of the defeated crusader from his torment, but waited patiently before acting.<br>
<br>
“So you were unable to obtain the dagger then, and that is the reason for your punishment?”  Asked Sarkokrul, smiling ever so slightly at the form before him.<br>
<br>
“I had obtained the dagger, young one, I was unable to make my escape from this infernal place, as you will be unable to do as well.” Came the tort reply. “I was captured by the Overseer of the crypt, and in torturing me for what seemed an eternity in their ways of mind and body control, forced me to tell them where I had hidden the dagger and slay my friend and companion Fodcod.”  Golin continued, his voice trailing off with obvious disappointment.  “Once they had the dagger again in their control, they shattered its blade and broke the hilt off and have distributed it amongst their mages so that it should not fall into our hands again, that is why you will fail.”<br>
<br>
Sarkokrul retrieved the broken metal shard from his pack and showed it to the guise of Golin before him. “So this is but one piece of the dagger then?” He queried, hoping to lead the ghostly figure to divulge all that he knew of the magical piece before he released the poor soul from its current plight.<br>
<br>
“Aye young one, it is.” Replied Golin, “Each of the Imprecators now has a part of the dagger, you have retrieved but one of the three.  And I am sure that the rest will be impossible to obtain by yourself.”<br>
<br>
Sarkokrul realized as did Talokrul at that moment, that Golin was unaware of the Shaman standing behind him, quietly watching the exchange unfold before him.<br>
<br>
Moving slightly to his right to ensure that the Shaman would not be noticed, Sarkokrul continued his verbal parry with the dead Crusader. “So how do they mend the pieces back into the dagger when they perform their ceremonies with it?”  Sarkokrul asked in anticipation of the final clue needed to direct his quest.<br>
<br>
“Far below the crypt in chambers next to the Overseer is a forge the Kly have built. Within it they forge many of their vile contraptions, and tools that control their slaves.  I have seen them use a special hammer, and when married with the three parts of the dagger, it is reborn into its pristine form.”   The floating ghost continued his story. “Only the blacksmith seems to be able to forge the dagger however.”<br>
<br>
Sarkokrul stepped back slightly preparing for the expected outcome of the exchange and asked one final question of the ghostly figure.  “So tell me fallen one, how do you relieve yourself of this spectral prison, you have so carelessly found yourself in?”<br>
<br>
A noticeable smile could be discerned growing on the face of the ghost Golin as he answered. “Why you are to take my place young one, didn’t you know?”  The form of the crusader moved perceptively towards Sarkokrul as he spoke. “Only by replacing my soul with that of another can I be free of this dreadful place and seek solace at the chair of Cazic Thule.”  The spectral form continued its slow perceptible approach towards the waiting Sarkokrul. <br>
<br>
Sarkokrul smiled in return. “If we are to feast on souls, then let us see who is the one to enjoy the meal.”<br>
<br>
The spectral crusader moved quickly towards Sarkokrul reaching though his body and wrapped his cold phantom fingers around the iksar’s heart.  Sarkokrul could feel the life force within in him begin to ebb.  As Golin began to smile at the demise of the young iksar, a forceful blast of cold enveloped him, forcing him to release his grasp, and turn to the now visible shaman behind him.<br>
<br>
As the specter turned towards Talokrul, Sarkokrul incanted briefly, his hands glowing in a familiar yellow glow, and stepped forward into the translucent shape draining what weak life forces remained within the tortured crusader.  The creature that was at one time Golin the crusader of Cabilis bellowed a curse at the two, as yet another forceful blast of freezing wind tore at the fragments of his form.<br>
<br>
Sarkokrul closed his eyes and focused on the ebbing ember of what would have been Golin’s heart and grasp it with his hand, unleashing the summoned force of Cazic Thule upon the undead soul.   Golin jerked in agony, his voice raspy and detached, as the curse against the two iksars gained in pitch and ferocity.<br>
<br>
Suddenly the room fell quiet, the spectral form of the crusader dissipating into the surrounding stale air.<br>
<br>
Sarkokrul lowered his hand from midair and spat on the floor where the ghost of Golin had stood moments before and uttered his own curse.  “May Cazic have more mercy on you than I, but I would not count on it.”<br>
<br>
Sarkokrul squatted back down and picked up the portions of rations which had fallen to the floor earlier, placing them back in the pack.  He now had the information he needed to find and return the mystical dagger to Lord Qyzar.  The lost crusader had been found and released from his torment as ordered.  <br>
<br>
Sarkokrul smiled to himself. “We shall see if I fail, perhaps, but your fate is not going to be mine.” He stated to the now stilled air around him.<br>
